children.subject: CS169 Software Engineering - at least with Prof Fox, you work with an actual client to build a web-application that serves the clients needs. You learn a lot of SE principles and have a live, actually used project at the end.

history.content:
I'll start a list of upper div classes I've taken and their projects here (others should add what I haven't had a chance to take, although I think this covers a majority of upper divs; missing 152, 17x where x > 0, 184, 189, 194-x)

ClassProject DescriptionTeamLanguage
CS150RISC-V Processor on a FPGA (remember that 61C Logisim project?) This project implements a processor in-hardware (now called CS151 I think?)2Verilog
CS160A mobile + smartwatch application of your (team's) choice~5Java
CS161Varies by instructor, but a lot of different projects revolving around real-world security exploits1-2Generally C
CS162Pintos: an operating system~5C
CS164

(Sen) A compiler in the "Classroom Object Oriented Language" (COOL) from (almost... not really) scratch

(Hilfinger) Different every semester; Ours was a weakly typed version of Python, somewhat similar to PHP Hack.

1-2Java when I took it
CS168I'm not sure if the projects vary, but lots of practical things with Shenker (DV routing, firewalls, etc.)1-2Python
CS169As mentioned below, a SaaS application with a real-world client5Ruby
CS170When I took 170, we did a final project where we competed to solve an NP-complete problem (this is an exception to the norm AFAIK though)1-2Any
CS186They're called homework assignments, but they're more like projects. Not as interesting as others, but this semester we implemented 2-phase locking1Python/SQL
CS188Implement AI concepts learned in class in a game of Pacman1-2Python

A number of the 194 classes have interesting projects as well
